GRADED PROJECT PYTHON - HONEY PRODUCTION

Attribute information
Slno Attribute Description
1. numcol Number of honey producing colonies.
2. yield percoly Honey yield per colony. (Unit is pounds)
3. total prod otal production (numcol x yieldpercol).(Unit is pounds)
4. price per lb Refers to average price per pound based on expanded sales. Unit is dollars.
5. Prodvalue Value of production (total prod x priceperlb). Unit is dollars.
6. Stocks Refers to stocks held by producers. Unit is pounds
7. Year Calendar year
8. State Different states' names.

6. Plot and understand the relationship between categorical variable 'year' and a numerical variable'prodvalue' through boxplot, and write your findings.
In [14]:
#the display of figure size which is of 10,5
plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
#it is from seaborn have taken boxplot with the year and prodvalue which dodge is true and color is blue
sns.boxplot(data = honey_df, x = "year",y = "prodvalue",dodge = True,color = "blue")
#it displays the title of the plot
plt.title("\n relationship b/w year & product value \n\n")
#it displays the x label of the plot
plt.xlabel("\nyear\n\n",loc='center')
#it displays the y label of the plot
plt.ylabel("product values")
#displays the ticks in 70 rotation
plt.xticks(rotation=70)
plt.tight_layout()#to adujust the spacing to prevent overlapping 
#it displays the plot
plt.show()

from the output of my inference are

  • The boxplot as the relationship between the categorical variable 'year' and the numerical variable 'prodvalue'.
  • The boxplot displays the distribution of 'prodvalue' for each year, thers is a compare of the median, quartiles, and potential outliers across different years.
  • by above plot we can understand how the value of production ('prodvalue') has varied over timeperiod of each year.
    • the following are the observation:
  • the median value of production as been appears to be relatively consistent across the diffrent years.
  • The interquartile range (IQR) also shows a similar spread for most years.
  • However, there seem to be some outliers present in certain years, represented as individual points beyond the whiskers of the boxplot.
  • The boxplot suggests that while the median and quartiles show a consistent pattern, there might be exceptional cases in specific years where the value of production deviates significantly from the norm.
  • for the Further investigation into the factors influencing these outliers and their impact on the overall trends in production would be valuable.
  • It is important to consider that the additional analysis, such as statistical measures and trend analysis, would be beneficial to gain deeper insights into the relationship between 'year' and 'prodvalue'.
7. Visualize and understand the relationship between the multiple pairs of variables throughout different years using pairplot and add your inferences. (use columns 'numcol', 'yield percol', 'total prod', 'prodvalue','year')
In [15]:
#it is display the figure of the figure size
plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
#we are mention list of columns
columns=['numcol', 'yieldpercol', 'totalprod', 'prodvalue','year']
#its displays from seaborn library a plot is mentioned as pairplot hue as years and pallete as Set3
pairplot=sns.pairplot(honey_df[columns],hue='year',palette='Set3')
#it displays the title of the plot which is of font size is 16
pairplot.fig.suptitle('\n relationship b/w variables by years',y=1.02,fontsize=16)
#it displays the pairplots
plt.show()

8. Display the correlation values using a plot and add your inferences. (use columns 'numcol', 'yield percol','total prod', 'stocks', 'price per lb', 'prodvalue')
In [16]:
#number of columns in list
columns=['numcol', 'yieldpercol', 'totalprod', 'prodvalue','stocks','priceperlb']
#calcualtion of correlated matrix with using a function of corr()
correlation_matrix=honey_df[columns].corr()
#it displays a figure of the plot size betweeen 10,5
plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
#the seaborn library represents teh heatmap to make the correlation using sns.heatmap which as cmap:it reflects color,vmin&vmax
sns.heatmap(correlation_matrix,annot=True,cmap='YlGnBu',vmin=1,vmax=1)
#it mentions the title of the plot
plt.title("the correlation matrix between variables")
#it displays the plot
plt.show()

from the output of my inference are

    these are the columns-'numcol', 'yieldpercol', 'totalprod', 'prodvalue','stocks','priceperlb'

  • The correlation matrix and heatmap display the correlation values between the selected columns.
  • The correlation coefficient ranges from -1 to 1, with 1 indicating a perfect positive correlation, -1 indicating perfect negative correlation, and 0 indicating no correlation.
    Based on the heatmap,the following inferences:
  • 'numcol' and 'yield percol': have a moderately positive correlation, suggesting that an increase in the number of colonies is associated with a higher yield per colony.
  • 'numcol' and 'total prod':have a strong positive correlation, indicating that a higher number of colonies leads to a larger total honey production.
  • 'numcol' and 'stocks':have a moderately positive correlation, suggesting that a higher number of colonies is associated with a larger stock of honey held by producers.
  • 'numcol' and 'pricelb':A negative correlation would indicate that as the number of colonies increases, the average price per pound decreases.
  • 'yield percol' and 'total prod'have a moderately positive correlation, indicating that a higher yield per colony leads to a larger total honey production.
  • 'yield percol' and 'stocks':have a weak positive correlation, suggesting that a higher yield per colony is associated with a slightly larger stock of honey held by producers.
  • 'total prod' and 'stocks':have a strong positive correlation, indicating that a larger total honey production is associated with a larger stock of honey held by producers.
  • 'price per lb' and 'prodvalue':have a weak negative correlation, suggesting that as the average price per pound decreases, the value of production tends to increase slightly.
